The number of reads are in a range that would be acceptable for an RNA-seq study (much more than the reads typically generated). However, this doesnt tell us very much about how useful the data are; do all the 30 million reads come from the same gene? Have we sequenced all the genes in the transcriptome? Are the counts roughly comparable between samples? To answer these questions we need to explore the counts in a bit more detail.

Sample-to-Sample comparisons

Visualising count distributions

We typically use a boxplot to visualise difference the distributions of the columns of a numeric data frame. We have previously created such plots using ggplot2. Unfortunately using ggplot2 to visualise our counts is not straightforward, so we will use the boxplot function from base R.

Applying the boxplot function to the raw counts from our dataset reveals something about the nature of the data; the distributions are dominated by a few genes with very large counts.

boxplot(counts(dds))

We can use the vst or rlog function from DESeq2to put the data on a more convenient scale for visualisation. It will also correct for some other features of the data that we will explore later.

# Get log2 counts
vsd <- vst(dds)
# Check distributions of samples using boxplots
boxplot(assay(vsd), xlab="", ylab="Log2 counts",las=2,main="Normalised Distributions")

The purpose of the boxplot is to check that we get the same distribution of counts for each sample. What this doesnt tell us is if the same gene measured on different samples is roughly the same.

This time we can use ggplot2 to plot the counts for one sample directly against the other.

library(ggplot2)
## make a data frame from the counts so we can plot with ggplot2
df <- data.frame(counts(dds))

ggplot(df, aes(x = `X1_CTR_BC_2`, y = `X4_CTR_BC_6`)) + geom_point()

Each individual dot on the plot is a gene and the x- and y- coordinates represent the counts in the two respective samples. It looks like the counts are reasonably well correlated to each other. This would expected as we have chosen two samples that belong to the same biological group. We can also use the same type of plot to compare samples from different groups.

ggplot(df, aes(x = `X1_CTR_BC_2`, y = `X2_TGF_BC_4`)) + geom_point()

The plot is possibly a bit noisier; hopefully reflecting the variability between the two samples. For the plots we have just made we could create corresponding statistics to quantify the degree of association. For example the correlation coefficient can be calculated using the cor function (see the exercises for this week).

Whilst such visualisations are useful in increasing our understanding of the data, we need a more automated approach to quality assessment. It would clearly be a lot of coding to create scatter plots for all pairwise combinations of samples. Our focus should be on interpreting the data; so any shortcuts we can take using existing functions in DESeq2 are desirable.

Principal components Analysis (PCA)

In genomic data, we have a large number of variables which are often highly correlated. (Principal Components Analysis) PCA is one of many dimension-reduction techniques that can remove redundancy and give a smaller more manageable set of variables. In summary it can help us to:-

  • Reduce dimensionality of the data
  • Decrease the redundancy of the data
  • Filter the noise in the data
  • Compress the data

See here for a nice explanation of PCA https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Jp4gsfOLMs

A PCA is an example of an unsupervised analysis, where we dont need to specify the groups. If your experiment is well-controlled and has worked well, what we hope to see is that the greatest sources of variation in the data correspond to the treatments/groups we are interested in. It is also an incredibly useful tool for quality control and checking for outliers.

DESeq2 has a convenient plotPCA function for making the PCA plot, which makes use of the ggplot2 graphics package.

plotPCA(vsd,intgroup="Treated")

There is also an option to return the values used in the plot for further exploration and customisation. Here we join the PCA results to the meta-data (sampleinfo) for plotting.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
pca_data <- plotPCA(vsd,intgroup="Treated",returnData = TRUE) %>% 
  dplyr::rename(Run = name) %>% 
  left_join(sampleInfo)
Joining, by = c("Treated", "Run")
  ggplot(pca_data,aes(x = PC1, y = PC2,col=Treated)) + geom_point()

Note about batch effects

In our unsupervised analysis we should see that the main source of variation is due to biological effects, and not technical variation such as when the libraries were sequenced. If we do observe high technical variation in our data, it is not a complete disaster provided that we have designed our experiment properly. In particular the sva Bioconductor package can correct for batch effects provided that representatives of the groups of interest appear in each batch. Alternatively, the batch or confounding factor may be incorporated into the differential expression analysis.

Below is an example of a PCA that might potentially worrying:-

Correcting the sample information

The person creating the sample sheet has been inconsistent about the way that values of Treated have been entered into the metadata. Such errors can be annoying when labeling plots, but have more serious consequences when attempting to fit statistical models to the data.

Here are a set of commands to create an updated sample sheet using the stringr package (part of tidyverse). We write a new file rather than over-writing the existing one.

library(stringr)
Warning: package stringr was built under R version 4.2.2
library(dplyr)
sampleInfo %>% 
mutate(condition = str_to_upper(condition)) %>% 
write_tsv(file="meta_data/sampleInfo_corrected.txt")

Visualising Gene-specific counts

The counts themselves can be obtained by using the counts function, which gives a matrix of values with one row for each gene and a column for each sample

We could potentially use this data in a plot to compare counts between groups, but once again DESeq2 provides a useful shortcut in the form of the plotCounts function. In this function we can specify a gene name of interest (which must be found somewhere in the row names of the count matrix) and a comparison (intgroup). The comparison name must be present in the sample information.

If you are unsure about what names can be used, you can retrieve the metadata that is stored with the DESeq dataset using the colData function.

The plot is not very inspiring, but it is a useful plot to quickly visualise the expression of a particular gene of interest (as we will see in the exercises it is possible to refine the plot using ggplot2). For example, we might have a gene identified in previous studies that we want to investigate.

Differential expression with DESeq2

Now that we are happy that we have normalised the data and that the quality looks good, we can continue to testing for differentially expressed genes. There are a number of packages to analyse RNA-Seq data. Most people use DESeq2 or edgeR. We will use DESeq2 for the rest of this practical.

It would be a good idea to save the results of the pre-processing so we dont have to repeat it every time.

dir.create("Robjects/",showWarnings = FALSE)
saveRDS(dds, file="Robjects/dds.rds")

The DESeq workflow in brief

We have previously defined the test condition using the design argument when we created the object. This can be checked using the design function.

Typically we decide the design for the analysis when we create the DESeq2 objects, but it can be modified prior to the differential expression analysis. The design tells DESeq2 which sample groups to compare in the differential analysis. The name specified must correspond to a column in the sample information.

colData(dds)
DataFrame with 9 rows and 5 columns

## note that the condition to be compared does not need to be in quote marks
design(dds) <- ~Treated

The counts that we have obtained via sequencing are subject to random sources of variation. The purpose of differential expression is to determine if potential sources of biological variation (e.g.counts observed from different sample groups) are greater than random noise.

The DESeq function runs a couple of processing steps automatically to adjust for different library size and gene-wise variability, which you can read about in the DESeq2 vignette and run some example code at the end of the next session.

de_treated<- DESeq(dds)

The results of the analysis are not immediately accessible, but can be obtained using the results function. Each row is a particular gene measured in the study (i.e.all genes in the organism being studied) and each column reports some aspect of the differential expression analysis for that gene. Note that all genes are reported. At this stage the gene identifiers are not very informative, something we will fix in the next section.

The output of results can tell us the direction of the contrast that is being calculated (i.e.which group is used as a baseline). In this case all fold-changes are calculated relative to un-treated, or CTRL samples - which makes sense. We can change the baseline of our comparison if we need to.

However, the output of results is not immediately useful. We would like to use the functions of dplyr to filter, sort and re-arrange the data. Fortunately, the authors have provided as argument that will output the results in a more useful format.

Appendix (Optional) Visualisting count distributions using ggplot2

In the practical we use the base R boxplot function to compare the distribution of counts between different samples. Why do we say it is not straightforward to plot these counts using ggplot2? Consider the dimensions of the count matrix:-

counts(dds) %>% head
                1_CTR_BC_2 2_TGF_BC_4 3_IR_BC_5 4_CTR_BC_6 5_TGF_BC_7 6_IR_BC_12
ENSG00000000003       1579       1547      1342       1704       1395       1264
ENSG00000000005          0          0         0          0          0          0
ENSG00000000419       1774       1775      1866       1809       1921       1776
ENSG00000000457        698        617       601        733        662        537
ENSG00000000460        246        309       116        224        255        108
ENSG00000000938         10          5        11          6          1          2
                7_CTR_BC_13 8_TGF_BC_14 9_IR_BC_15
ENSG00000000003        1556        1370       1269
ENSG00000000005           0           0          1
ENSG00000000419        1797        1482       1980
ENSG00000000457         751         593        628
ENSG00000000460         245         289        127
ENSG00000000938          19           4          8

And the format that the code to create a boxplot is usually written in

ggplot(data, aes(x = ...., y=....)) + geom_boxplot()

Take a bit of time to consider this before moving-on. You do not need to write any code.

The issue is that the count matrix is in wide rather than long format. In other words, the counts for a particular gene go across the table rather than down. This present a problem for ggplot2. We can convert using one of the tools from tidyr. For more information on tidyr, see the package website

  • https://tidyr.tidyverse.org/

The format of data required is something like

Gene Sample Expression
A Sample1 10.3
A Sample2 20.5

First we have to convert the counts from a matrix to a data frame.

counts(dds) %>% 
  as.data.frame

The pivot_longer function will do the task of converting from wide to long data. The arguments; which columns we have to convert (all in this case) and what we want to respective value and name columns to be.

library(tidyr)
Warning: package tidyr was built under R version 4.2.1
Attaching package: tidyr

The following object is masked from package:S4Vectors:

    expand
counts(dds) %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols=1:9,values_to="Expression",names_to="Sample")

The data can then be passed directly to ggplot for plotting.

library(tidyr)
counts(dds) %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols=1:9,values_to="Expression",names_to="Sample") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Sample, y = Expression)) + geom_boxplot()

As we saw, the plot isnt particularly informative due to the scale. Instead we can plot the variance-stabilized counts using similar code

library(tidyr)
assay(vsd) %>% 
  as.data.frame %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols=1:9,values_to="Expression",names_to="Sample") %>%
